('cs-prem-0001-septic-shock','nclex','case_study','sepsis_septic_shock','Evolving septic shock',4,
'After the 30 mL/kg crystalloid bolus the client''s MAP is still 58 mm Hg, lactate has risen from 3.2 to 4.6 mmol/L, and urine output is 15 mL/hr. Which action should the nurse anticipate next?',
'Septic shock — fluid-refractory hypotension',
'A 64-year-old with pyelonephritis arrived febrile (39.4 C), HR 124, BP 84/48, RR 26, mottled knees. Blood cultures were drawn, broad-spectrum antibiotics started, and a 30 mL/kg normal saline bolus completed. The nurse is reassessing.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Initiate a norepinephrine infusion to target MAP >= 65 mm Hg"},{"id":"b","text":"Give a second 30 mL/kg bolus and continue to reassess in an hour"},{"id":"c","text":"Administer a loop diuretic to improve the low urine output"},{"id":"d","text":"Hold further intervention since antibiotics are already infusing"}]',
'a',
'Hypotension persisting after adequate fluid resuscitation defines fluid-refractory septic shock, which requires vasopressors. Norepinephrine is the first-line agent to restore MAP >= 65 mm Hg and organ perfusion.',
'This client now meets the definition of septic shock: persistent hypotension (MAP 58) and rising lactate (4.6) despite a complete 30 mL/kg crystalloid bolus, signaling ongoing tissue hypoperfusion. The Surviving Sepsis Campaign directs that fluid-refractory shock be treated with vasopressors, and norepinephrine is first-line because it raises MAP through balanced alpha-1 vasoconstriction with modest beta-1 support, without the excess tachyarrhythmia of dopamine. The decisive cue is the trend: a climbing lactate plus oliguria means perfusion is worsening, not improving. A second large bolus risks pulmonary edema with little hemodynamic gain once the patient is fluid-refractory; a diuretic would deepen hypovolemia and is contraindicated; and doing nothing ignores active deterioration. Pearl: when MAP stays below 65 after adequate fluids, the answer is pressors and a central line, not more volume.',
'{"b":"Once shock is fluid-refractory, additional large boluses yield diminishing returns and risk pulmonary edema; vasopressors are indicated.","c":"The oliguria is from hypoperfusion, not volume overload — a diuretic would worsen hypovolemia and perfusion.","d":"Antibiotics treat the source but do not correct acute hypotension; perfusion must be restored now with vasopressors."}',
'[{"title":"Surviving Sepsis Campaign 2021","citation":"Vasopressors for fluid-refractory septic shock; norepinephrine first-line, MAP target >= 65."}]',
'["case_study","sepsis","perfusion","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0002-dka-potassium','nclex','case_study','dka_management','DKA insulin-readiness check',4,
'The provider orders an insulin infusion. Before starting it, which laboratory value most requires the nurse''s attention?',
'DKA — pre-insulin safety check',
'A 22-year-old with type 1 diabetes presents with glucose 548 mg/dL, pH 7.19, HCO3 12, and Kussmaul respirations. Initial labs: potassium 3.3 mEq/L, sodium 134, creatinine 1.1. Normal saline is infusing.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Potassium 3.3 mEq/L"},{"id":"b","text":"Sodium 134 mEq/L"},{"id":"c","text":"Creatinine 1.1 mg/dL"},{"id":"d","text":"Bicarbonate 12 mEq/L"}]',
'a',
'Insulin drives potassium intracellularly and can cause life-threatening hypokalemia. With a potassium already low at 3.3, insulin must be withheld and potassium repleted (typically until K >= 3.3-3.5) before the infusion begins.',
'In DKA, total-body potassium is always depleted from osmotic diuresis even when the serum value looks normal or high, because acidosis shifts K+ out of cells. This client is already frankly hypokalemic at 3.3 — starting insulin would drive potassium into cells and can precipitate fatal ventricular arrhythmia. Standard protocol holds insulin until potassium is at least 3.3-3.5 mEq/L and replacement is underway. The other values, while abnormal, do not change the immediate next step: the low sodium is partly dilutional from hyperglycemia, the creatinine is near normal, and the low bicarbonate reflects the acidosis that insulin and fluids will correct over time. Pearl: in DKA, fluids first, never start insulin until you know the potassium, and replace K+ before insulin whenever it is below ~3.3.',
'{"b":"The sodium is mildly low and partly a dilutional artifact of hyperglycemia; it does not gate insulin initiation.","c":"A creatinine of 1.1 is near normal and not the immediate safety concern before insulin.","d":"The low bicarbonate reflects the ketoacidosis itself, which fluids and insulin will correct; it is not the pre-insulin gate."}',
'[{"title":"ADA Standards of Care — Hyperglycemic Crises","citation":"Hold insulin until K >= 3.3 mEq/L; replace potassium first."}]',
'["case_study","endocrine","DKA","potassium","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0003-icp-herniation','nclex','case_study','increased_icp','Neuro deterioration — Cushing triad',4,
'The client''s vitals shift to BP 188/62 mm Hg, HR 48, and irregular respirations, with a newly sluggish right pupil. Which is the nurse''s priority action?',
'Traumatic brain injury — rising ICP',
'A 30-year-old admitted after a fall has a closed head injury. Over an hour the GCS drops from 14 to 9. The nurse rechecks vitals and pupils.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Notify the provider/rapid response immediately and prepare for emergent ICP-lowering measures"},{"id":"b","text":"Recheck the blood pressure in 30 minutes and continue routine monitoring"},{"id":"c","text":"Administer the scheduled antihypertensive to treat the high blood pressure"},{"id":"d","text":"Lay the client flat to improve cerebral perfusion"}]',
'a',
'Widening pulse pressure with hypertension, bradycardia, and irregular respirations is Cushing''s triad — a late sign of dangerously elevated ICP and impending herniation. This is an emergency requiring immediate escalation and ICP-lowering interventions.',
'The combination of a rising systolic pressure with a widening pulse pressure, bradycardia, and irregular (often Cheyne-Stokes or ataxic) respirations is Cushing''s triad, the brainstem''s reflex response to critically high intracranial pressure as cerebral perfusion fails. Coupled with a falling GCS and a new sluggish/dilating pupil (early uncal herniation compressing CN III), this is a neurosurgical emergency. The nurse must escalate immediately and anticipate ICP-lowering measures: elevate the head of bed 30 degrees midline, ensure normocapnia or brief controlled hyperventilation per order, hyperosmolar therapy (mannitol or hypertonic saline), and emergent imaging/neurosurgery. The hypertension is a compensatory response to preserve cerebral perfusion pressure — treating it with an antihypertensive would drop CPP and worsen ischemia. Laying the client flat raises ICP. Pearl: Cushing''s triad is a late, ominous sign; act on the trend (falling GCS, new pupil change) before the triad fully appears.',
'{"b":"A 30-minute recheck delays care during active herniation — this requires immediate escalation.","c":"The hypertension is compensatory to maintain cerebral perfusion pressure; lowering it would reduce CPP and worsen ischemia.","d":"Lying flat increases intracranial pressure; the head should be elevated 30 degrees and midline."}',
'[{"title":"Brain Trauma Foundation Guidelines","citation":"ICP/CPP management; Cushing triad signifies impending herniation."}]',
'["case_study","neuro","ICP","emergency","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0004-pph-atony','nclex','case_study','postpartum_hemorrhage','Postpartum hemorrhage — first action',3,
'One hour after a vaginal birth the nurse notes a saturated peripad in 10 minutes and a fundus that is boggy and deviated to the right. Which action should the nurse take first?',
'Immediate postpartum — heavy bleeding',
'A 28-year-old gravida 4 delivered a 4,100 g infant after a prolonged labor with oxytocin augmentation. Vital signs: BP 104/62, HR 98.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Perform firm fundal massage and assist the client to empty her bladder"},{"id":"b","text":"Administer a PRN analgesic for afterbirth cramping"},{"id":"c","text":"Document the findings and reassess at the next routine check"},{"id":"d","text":"Place the client in reverse Trendelenburg position"}]',
'a',
'A boggy, displaced fundus with heavy bleeding indicates uterine atony, the leading cause of early postpartum hemorrhage. The first nursing actions are firm fundal massage and emptying a full bladder, which displaces and prevents the uterus from contracting.',
'Uterine atony causes 70-80% of early postpartum hemorrhage; this client carries multiple risk factors — grand multiparity, a macrosomic infant, prolonged oxytocin-augmented labor — all of which overdistend and fatigue the myometrium. The classic findings are a soft (boggy) fundus that is often displaced upward and to the right by a full bladder, with brisk bleeding. The immediate, highest-yield nursing action is firm fundal massage to stimulate contraction, plus emptying the bladder because a distended bladder mechanically prevents the uterus from clamping down on the spiral arteries. If massage and bladder emptying fail, escalate to uterotonics (oxytocin, then methylergonovine — avoid in hypertension — or carboprost — avoid in asthma). A normal-ish blood pressure can be falsely reassuring early because young patients compensate until they suddenly decompensate. Pearl: for a boggy fundus, massage and empty the bladder before reaching for any medication.',
'{"b":"Analgesia does not address active hemorrhage from atony and wastes critical time.","c":"Heavy bleeding with a boggy fundus is an emergency, not a routine-recheck finding.","d":"Positioning does not treat atony; fundal massage and bladder emptying are the first actions."}',
'[{"title":"AWHONN Postpartum Hemorrhage Practice Guidelines","citation":"Uterine atony first-line: fundal massage, empty bladder, uterotonics."}]',
'["case_study","OB","postpartum_hemorrhage","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0005-epiglottitis','nclex','case_study','pediatric_airway','Pediatric epiglottitis — what to avoid',4,
'A 4-year-old presents drooling, leaning forward in a tripod position, with a muffled voice, high fever, and stridor. Which action is contraindicated?',
'Suspected epiglottitis',
'The unimmunized child suddenly became ill over a few hours. The child appears anxious and will not lie down. SpO2 is 93% on room air.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Examine the throat with a tongue depressor to visualize the epiglottis"},{"id":"b","text":"Keep the child calm and in a position of comfort with a parent present"},{"id":"c","text":"Notify the provider and prepare for emergent airway management"},{"id":"d","text":"Administer humidified oxygen as tolerated without agitating the child"}]',
'a',
'In suspected epiglottitis, examining the throat with a tongue depressor can trigger laryngospasm and complete airway obstruction. The throat must NOT be inspected until a definitive airway can be secured in a controlled setting.',
'The clinical picture — abrupt high fever, drooling, dysphagia, muffled ("hot potato") voice, tripod positioning, and stridor in an unimmunized child — is classic epiglottitis, an airway emergency caused by inflammation of the supraglottic structures (historically H. influenzae type b). The single most important nursing principle is to avoid anything that agitates the child or stimulates the already-swollen epiglottis, because crying, supine positioning, or instrumentation can precipitate complete laryngospasm and total obstruction. Therefore inspecting the throat with a tongue blade is contraindicated; visualization is performed only in the OR with anesthesia and ENT ready to secure an airway. Correct actions keep the child calm with a parent, deliver blow-by oxygen without distress, and mobilize the team for controlled intubation. Pearl: in suspected epiglottitis, hands off the airway and no tongue blade — keep the child calm and get definitive airway backup.',
'{"b":"Keeping the child calm in a position of comfort is correct and reduces the risk of obstruction.","c":"Mobilizing the provider and airway team is appropriate and expected.","d":"Non-agitating humidified oxygen is appropriate supportive care."}',
'[{"title":"AAP Red Book / PALS","citation":"Epiglottitis: avoid airway stimulation and throat inspection until airway secured."}]',
'["case_study","pediatric","airway","emergency","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0006-acs-priority','nclex','case_study','acute_coronary_syndrome','ACS — initial priority',3,
'A 58-year-old reports crushing substernal chest pain radiating to the left jaw, diaphoresis, and nausea that began 30 minutes ago. After applying oxygen for hypoxia, which action should the nurse prioritize?',
'Acute chest pain — possible STEMI',
'Vital signs: BP 148/90, HR 96, RR 22, SpO2 92% on room air (now on 2 L nasal cannula). The client has a history of hypertension and smoking.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Obtain a 12-lead ECG and notify the provider"},{"id":"b","text":"Administer a stat dose of IV morphine for the pain"},{"id":"c","text":"Send the client for a treadmill stress test"},{"id":"d","text":"Encourage the client to rest and reassess pain in one hour"}]',
'a',
'A 12-lead ECG within 10 minutes is the priority for suspected ACS because it determines whether the client is having a STEMI requiring emergent reperfusion. Time-to-ECG drives all subsequent decisions.',
'Acute coronary syndrome management is time-critical, and the guideline standard is to obtain a 12-lead ECG within 10 minutes of presentation with ischemic-type chest pain. The ECG is the pivotal branch point: ST-elevation (STEMI) mandates emergent reperfusion (PCI within 90 minutes or fibrinolytics), whereas a non-ST-elevation picture follows a different antithrombotic/risk-stratification pathway. While the MONA-type interventions (aspirin, nitroglycerin, oxygen for hypoxia, and morphine for refractory pain) are part of care, none of them can be correctly sequenced until the ECG defines the diagnosis — and aspirin, not morphine, is the priority medication. A stress test is absolutely contraindicated during active chest pain. Telling the client to rest and reassess in an hour ignores an evolving infarction. Pearl: for ischemic chest pain, the clock starts immediately — ECG within 10 minutes and aspirin come before analgesia.',
'{"b":"Morphine is for pain refractory to nitrates and is not the first priority; aspirin and the diagnostic ECG come first.","c":"A stress test is contraindicated during active chest pain — it could provoke a lethal event.","d":"Delaying assessment for an hour risks ongoing myocardial necrosis; time is muscle."}',
'[{"title":"AHA/ACC ACS Guidelines","citation":"12-lead ECG within 10 minutes; aspirin early; reperfusion for STEMI."}]',
'["case_study","cardiac","ACS","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0007-anaphylaxis','nclex','case_study','anaphylaxis','Anaphylaxis — first drug',4,
'Minutes into an IV antibiotic infusion, a client develops lip swelling, diffuse hives, wheezing, and a BP of 82/40. Which medication should the nurse administer first?',
'Acute anaphylaxis during infusion',
'The nurse has stopped the antibiotic. The client is anxious, with audible wheeze and a feeling of throat tightness.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Intramuscular epinephrine 0.3-0.5 mg (1 mg/mL) into the lateral thigh"},{"id":"b","text":"Intravenous diphenhydramine"},{"id":"c","text":"Intravenous methylprednisolone"},{"id":"d","text":"Nebulized albuterol"}]',
'a',
'Epinephrine is the first-line, life-saving treatment for anaphylaxis and must be given immediately IM into the vastus lateralis. Antihistamines, steroids, and bronchodilators are adjuncts that do not reverse airway edema or shock.',
'Anaphylaxis is a rapidly progressive, IgE-mediated systemic reaction; the presence of mucocutaneous signs (lip swelling, hives) PLUS respiratory compromise (wheeze, throat tightness) and hypotension confirms it. Epinephrine is the only first-line treatment that addresses every life-threatening mechanism at once: alpha-1 vasoconstriction reverses hypotension and mucosal/airway edema, while beta-2 effects relieve bronchospasm and beta-1 effects support cardiac output. It is given IM into the anterolateral thigh (vastus lateralis) for fastest reliable absorption and is repeated every 5-15 minutes as needed. Diphenhydramine and steroids have slow onset and treat only cutaneous/late-phase symptoms — they are adjuncts, never the priority. Albuterol helps bronchospasm but does nothing for shock or airway edema. Delaying epinephrine to give an antihistamine first is a classic fatal error. Pearl: anaphylaxis = epinephrine IM now; everything else is secondary.',
'{"b":"Diphenhydramine has slow onset and treats only cutaneous symptoms; it does not reverse airway edema or shock.","c":"Corticosteroids prevent late-phase reactions but take hours to act and are not the immediate life-saving drug.","d":"Albuterol relieves bronchospasm only and does not address hypotension or laryngeal edema."}',
'[{"title":"AAAAI/WAO Anaphylaxis Guidelines","citation":"IM epinephrine is first-line; antihistamines and steroids are adjuncts."}]',
'["case_study","anaphylaxis","pharmacology","emergency","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0008-hyperkalemia-ecg','nclex','case_study','hyperkalemia','Hyperkalemia — first priority',4,
'A client with CKD has a potassium of 7.1 mEq/L and the monitor shows peaked T waves with a widening QRS. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate administering first?',
'Severe hyperkalemia with ECG changes',
'The client missed two dialysis sessions. Vital signs: BP 150/88, HR 58 and irregular. IV access is patent.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"IV calcium gluconate"},{"id":"b","text":"IV regular insulin with dextrose"},{"id":"c","text":"Oral sodium polystyrene sulfonate"},{"id":"d","text":"Schedule the client for urgent hemodialysis"}]',
'a',
'With hyperkalemic ECG changes (peaked T waves, widening QRS), IV calcium is given first to stabilize the cardiac membrane and prevent lethal arrhythmia. It does not lower potassium but buys time for potassium-shifting and removal therapies.',
'A potassium of 7.1 with peaked T waves and a widening QRS signals imminent risk of sine-wave pattern, ventricular fibrillation, or asystole. The treatment sequence is mechanism-driven: first STABILIZE the myocardium with IV calcium gluconate (or chloride), which raises the cardiac depolarization threshold and protects against lethal arrhythmia within minutes — though it does not change the serum potassium. Next, SHIFT potassium intracellularly with IV insulin plus dextrose (and often a beta-agonist), which works in 15-30 minutes. Finally, REMOVE potassium from the body with dialysis (definitive in CKD), and/or a GI cation exchanger (slow). The decisive cue is the ECG: when membrane instability is present, cardiac protection comes before potassium-lowering. Dialysis is the definitive fix here but takes time to arrange, so calcium bridges the gap. Pearl: hyperkalemia with ECG changes — calcium first to protect the heart, then shift, then remove.',
'{"b":"Insulin/dextrose shifts potassium intracellularly but takes 15-30 minutes; the heart needs membrane stabilization first.","c":"Cation exchangers act slowly over hours and are not the emergency intervention for ECG changes.","d":"Dialysis is definitive but cannot be initiated instantly; calcium protects the myocardium while it is arranged."}',
'[{"title":"KDIGO / ACLS Hyperkalemia","citation":"Stabilize (calcium) -> shift (insulin/dextrose, beta-agonist) -> remove (dialysis)."}]',
'["case_study","electrolyte","hyperkalemia","renal","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0009-gi-bleed-shock','nclex','case_study','gi_bleed_shock','Upper GI bleed — hypovolemic shock',3,
'A client with cirrhosis vomits a large amount of bright red blood. Vitals: BP 86/50, HR 122, cool clammy skin, and growing restlessness. After ensuring airway and calling for help, which action should the nurse prioritize?',
'Variceal hemorrhage',
'The client has known esophageal varices. Two large-bore IVs are being placed. The client is anxious and pale.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Begin rapid infusion of isotonic crystalloid and obtain type and crossmatch"},{"id":"b","text":"Administer the scheduled oral beta blocker for portal hypertension"},{"id":"c","text":"Position the client upright and offer oral fluids"},{"id":"d","text":"Obtain a stool sample for occult blood testing"}]',
'a',
'This is hypovolemic shock from variceal hemorrhage. The priority is rapid volume resuscitation with isotonic fluid through large-bore access while blood products are readied via type and crossmatch.',
'Hematemesis of bright red blood with hypotension, tachycardia, cool clammy skin, and restlessness (an early sign of cerebral hypoperfusion) is hypovolemic/hemorrhagic shock from a likely variceal bleed in this cirrhotic patient. After securing the airway (aspiration risk is high with active hematemesis) and calling for help, the priority is aggressive volume resuscitation through two large-bore IVs with isotonic crystalloid while type and crossmatch is sent so blood products can follow quickly; massive transfusion protocols and octreotide/endoscopy come next. An oral beta blocker is for chronic prevention of variceal bleeding, not acute hemorrhage, and giving anything by mouth is unsafe during active vomiting and shock. Occult blood testing is irrelevant when frank hemorrhage is obvious and wastes time. Pearl: in active hemorrhagic shock, the priority is volume and blood through large-bore access — not chronic medications or confirmatory tests.',
'{"b":"Oral beta blockers prevent future variceal bleeds; they have no role in acute hemorrhage and cannot be given safely during hematemesis.","c":"Oral fluids are contraindicated during active vomiting and shock (aspiration); upright positioning can worsen hypotension.","d":"Occult blood testing is pointless with obvious frank bleeding and delays resuscitation."}',
'[{"title":"AASLD Variceal Hemorrhage Guidelines","citation":"Resuscitate with crystalloid/blood, airway protection, octreotide, urgent endoscopy."}]',
'["case_study","GI","shock","hemorrhage","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0010-suicide-safety','nclex','case_study','suicide_risk','Acute suicide risk — priority',4,
'During admission a client states, "I have a bottle of pills at home and tonight feels like the right time to use them." Which is the nurse''s priority action?',
'Acute suicidal ideation with plan',
'The client was brought in by a family member for worsening depression. The client is calm but expresses hopelessness and has a specific plan and means.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Ensure one-to-one continuous observation and a safe environment immediately"},{"id":"b","text":"Schedule a psychiatry consult for the following morning"},{"id":"c","text":"Encourage the client to focus on positive coping strategies"},{"id":"d","text":"Respect the client''s privacy and allow time alone to process feelings"}]',
'a',
'A client with active suicidal ideation, a specific plan, and access to means is at imminent risk. The priority is immediate safety: one-to-one observation and removal of any means of self-harm.',
'Risk stratification in suicidality hinges on ideation plus a plan plus available means plus intent — this client has all four (a specific method, access to pills, and a stated timeframe), placing them at imminent, high acute risk. The overriding nursing priority is physical safety NOW: initiate continuous one-to-one (constant) observation, remove potential means of self-harm from the environment, and never leave the client alone. Safety precedes therapeutic dialogue, consults, or coping work — all of which matter but none of which protect the client in the next minutes. Deferring psychiatry to the morning leaves a high-risk client unmonitored overnight; promoting coping strategies or allowing privacy/time alone is actively dangerous when intent and means are present. Pearl: when ideation is paired with a plan and means, maintain constant observation and a means-restricted environment before anything else.',
'{"b":"A morning consult leaves an imminently high-risk client unprotected overnight; safety is needed now.","c":"Coping strategies are valuable later but do not protect a client with an active plan and means right now.","d":"Allowing time alone is contraindicated for an actively suicidal client with means — constant observation is required."}',
'[{"title":"Joint Commission NPSG / SAMHSA","citation":"Suicide risk with plan and means requires immediate 1:1 observation and means restriction."}]',
'["case_study","psychosocial","suicide_safety","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch());
